<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>CSIR PYQ Unit IV Q1 — Degree [Q(√2,√3):Q]</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[The degree \([\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3}):\mathbb{Q}]\) is:]]></text>
  </questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: 4.</strong><br>\([\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}):\mathbb{Q}]=2\). Since \(\sqrt{3}\notin\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\) (its minimal polynomial \(x^2-3\) remains irreducible over \(\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\)), we get \([\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3}):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})]=2\). By the tower law, \([\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3}):\mathbb{Q}]=2\cdot 2=4\).</p>]]></text>
  </generalfeedback>
