<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>CSIR PYQ Unit IV Q11 — Splitting field of x³−2</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[The degree of the splitting field of \(x^3-2\) over \(\mathbb{Q}\) is:]]></text>
  </questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: 6.</strong><br>The roots of \(x^3-2\) are \(\sqrt[3]{2},\,\omega\sqrt[3]{2},\,\omega^2\sqrt[3]{2}\) where \(\omega=e^{2\pi i/3}\). The splitting field is \(\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2},\omega)\). We have \([\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2}):\mathbb{Q}]=3\) and \([\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2},\omega):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2})]=2\) (since \(\omega\notin\mathbb{R}\)). Total degree: \(3\times 2=6\).</p>]]></text>
  </generalfeedback>
