  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: Algebraic.</strong><br>If \([K:F]=n\), then for any \(\alpha\in K\), the \(n+1\) elements \(1,\alpha,\alpha^2,\ldots,\alpha^n\) are linearly dependent over \(F\). So \(\alpha\) satisfies some non-zero polynomial over \(F\), i.e., \(\alpha\) is algebraic over \(F\). The converse is false: \(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}/\mathbb{Q}\) is algebraic but infinite.</p>]]></text>
